Ran across this while reviewing the netting code.

To grab the lower 8 bits should be `(x & 0xff)`, not `(x & 0x01)`. For
`v` in `[0, 1]` (old versions of geth) this should cause an issue but
for `v` in `[27, 28]`, the value of v will be reversed (the resulting
value of `v` will be `(27 & 1) + 27 == 28`, or `(28 & 1) + 27 == 27`).

Reviewing the asm output using `solc --asm NettingChannelLibrary.sol` seems to produce the correct code:
```
        /* "raiden/smart_contracts/NettingChannelLibrary.sol":19105:19109  0xff */
      0xff
        /* "raiden/smart_contracts/NettingChannelLibrary.sol":19099:19101  65 */
      0x41
        /* "raiden/smart_contracts/NettingChannelLibrary.sol":19088:19097  signature */
      dup6
        /* "raiden/smart_contracts/NettingChannelLibrary.sol":19084:19087  add */
      add
        /* "raiden/smart_contracts/NettingChannelLibrary.sol":19078:19083  mload */
      mload
        /* "raiden/smart_contracts/NettingChannelLibrary.sol":19074:19077  and */
      and
        /* "raiden/smart_contracts/NettingChannelLibrary.sol":19069:19110  v := and(mload(add(signature, 65)), 0xff) */
      swap1
      pop
```

This allows to do stuff like this:

```
{% if obj.val %}
  <p>{{ obj.val }}</p>
{% endif %}
```
